var documenterSearchIndex = {"docs":
[{"category":"section","location":"concepts/threading/#Threading","page":"Threading","text":"PhreeqcRM parallelizes the RunCells loop with OpenMP — each OMP thread runs reactions on its own subset of cells using a dedicated worker IPhreeqc. Julia has its own thread pool. Combining the two naively gives nthreads_julia × nthreads_omp workers contending for cores.\n\nThe constructor takes nthreads (OpenMP threads) and defaults to 1 so you don't accidentally oversubscribe. It also warns if Threads.nthreads() * nthreads > Sys.CPU_THREADS.","title":"Threading"},{"category":"section","location":"concepts/threading/#Three-patterns","page":"Threading","text":"","title":"Three patterns"},{"category":"section","location":"concepts/threading/#A-—-Single-instance,-OMP-for-reactions-(default)","page":"Threading","text":"rm = PhreeqcRMInstance(nxyz; nthreads = Threads.nthreads())\nfor step in 1:nsteps\n    transport!(c)                    # serial Julia\n    set_concentrations!(rm, c)\n    set_time!(rm, step*dt); set_time_step!(rm, dt)\n    run_cells!(rm)                   # parallel via OpenMP\n    get_concentrations!(rm, c)\nend\n\nSimplest. Best when reactions dominate runtime.","title":"A — Single instance, OMP for reactions (default)"},{"category":"section","location":"concepts/threading/#B-—-Domain-decomposition,-multiple-instances,-Julia-threads","page":"Threading","text":"nchunks = Threads.nthreads()\nchunks  = collect(Iterators.partition(1:nxyz, cld(nxyz, nchunks)))\nrms = [PhreeqcRMInstance(length(c); nthreads = 1) for c in chunks]   # OMP off\n# ... per-instance setup ...\ncs = [zeros_concentrations(rm) for rm in rms]\nfor step in 1:nsteps\n    transport_with_halo_exchange!(cs, chunks)\n    Threads.@threads for i in eachindex(rms)\n        set_concentrations!(rms[i], cs[i])\n        run_cells!(rms[i])\n        get_concentrations!(rms[i], cs[i])\n    end\nend\n\nBetter when transport is memory-bound or when you want Julia-thread parallelism across the full step (not just reactions).","title":"B — Domain decomposition, multiple instances, Julia threads"},{"category":"section","location":"concepts/threading/#C-—-Single-instance-Julia-threads-for-I/O","page":"Threading","text":"rm = PhreeqcRMInstance(nxyz; nthreads = max(1, Threads.nthreads() - 1))\nout_chan = Channel{NamedTuple}(8)\nwriter = Threads.@spawn for snap in out_chan; save_to_disk(snap); end\n\nfor step in 1:nsteps\n    transport!(c)\n    set_concentrations!(rm, c); run_cells!(rm); get_concentrations!(rm, c)\n    put!(out_chan, get_selected_output(rm))\nend\nclose(out_chan); wait(writer)\n\nUseful in production runs where I/O or post-processing would otherwise serialize behind reactions.","title":"C — Single instance + Julia threads for I/O"},{"category":"section","location":"concepts/threading/#Safety-contract","page":"Threading","text":"Within one instance: only one RM_* call at a time. PhreeqcRM parallelizes RunCells internally; firing two RM_* calls on the same instance from two Julia threads is undefined behavior.\nAcross instances: independent instances can be driven from independent Julia threads concurrently. The :threads test tier verifies this — two instances driven from two Julia threads produce results matching the serial baseline.","title":"Safety contract"},{"category":"section","location":"concepts/threading/#macOS-note","page":"Threading","text":"macOS clang doesn't ship omp.h. The build script installs libomp from Homebrew automatically; without it, the dylib falls back to single-threaded and thread_count(rm) returns 1 regardless of the requested nthreads.","title":"macOS note"},{"category":"section","location":"concepts/lifecycle/#Lifecycle-and-call-order","page":"Lifecycle","text":"PhreeqcRM is stateful: some calls must come before others or they silently do the wrong thing.","title":"Lifecycle & call order"},{"category":"section","location":"concepts/lifecycle/#The-mandatory-order","page":"Lifecycle","text":"PhreeqcRMInstance(nxyz; ...)         (1)  Create + SetComponentH2O\n  ↓\nload_database!(rm, \"phreeqc.dat\")    (2)  database elements + log K\n  ↓\nrun_file!(rm, \"input.pqi\")           (3)  parse SOLUTION / EXCHANGE / RATES etc.\n  ↓\nfind_components!(rm)                 (4)  discover components → fixes ncomps\n  ↓\nset_mapping!(rm, ...)                (5)  optional; default identity\nset_units!(rm; solution = ..., ...)        (6)  solution unit is required\nset_porosity!(rm, ...) etc.          (7)  per-cell physics\n  ↓\nset_initial_conditions!(rm; ...)     (8)  assign numbered reactant blocks\n  ↓\nset_time!(rm, t)                     (9a) before run_cells! or kinetics step 0\nset_time_step!(rm, dt)               (9b) before run_cells!\n  ↓\nrun_cells!(rm)                       (10) per-cell reaction step\nget_concentrations!(rm, c)           (11) pull results\n  ↓\nclose(rm)                            (12) preferred teardown","title":"The mandatory order"},{"category":"section","location":"concepts/lifecycle/#Why-each-rule-matters","page":"Lifecycle","text":"Rule Failure mode if violated\ncomponent_h2o on constructor (before load_database!) Database parses elements without separating water, ncomps will be wrong\nload_database! before run_file! Script references elements that aren't defined yet\nrun_file! before find_components! InitialPhreeqc is empty, ncomps = 0\nfind_components! before zeros_concentrations / set_concentrations! Concentration buffer would be sized 0 × nxyz\nset_units!(...; solution=...) before set_concentrations! Numeric values silently misinterpreted (mol/L treated as mg/L, etc.)\nset_time! + set_time_step! before run_cells! Kinetics integrate over zero time, no kinetic effect\nclose(rm) before drop OK — finalizer is a safety net, but join-on-OMP-threads at GC time is risky","title":"Why each rule matters"},{"category":"section","location":"concepts/lifecycle/#Teardown","page":"Lifecycle","text":"close(rm) is the documented teardown. It's idempotent — repeated calls are no-ops after the first. The finalizer calls close(rm) as a safety net if the handle is dropped without closing, but don't rely on it: RM_Destroy joins on internal OpenMP threads, which is not something you want firing from arbitrary GC contexts.\n\nPhreeqcRM.with_instance is the preferred RAII-style pattern:\n\nPhreeqcRM.with_instance(40; nthreads = 4) do rm\n    load_database!(rm, \"phreeqc.dat\")\n    # ... work ...\nend   # close() called even if the block throws","title":"Teardown"},{"category":"section","location":"concepts/memory_model/#Memory-model-and-array-layout","page":"Memory & layout","text":"PhreeqcRM never returns malloc'd memory the caller has to free. Every array crossing the boundary is caller-allocated on both sides of the call:\n\nPattern Who allocates Who fills Examples\nCaller-allocated, callee-reads caller library copies into its internal store set_porosity!, set_concentrations!\nCaller-allocated, callee-writes caller library writes into the buffer get_concentrations!, get_selected_output, error strings","title":"Memory model & array layout"},{"category":"section","location":"concepts/memory_model/#Concentration-matrix-layout","page":"Memory & layout","text":"The library packs the concentration buffer with the cell index varying fastest and the component index slowest:\n\nbuf[i_cell + nxyz * i_comp]    // C-side\n\nThe Julia shape that matches this with zero copying is Matrix{Float64}(nxyz, ncomps):\n\nEach row is one cell.\nEach column is one component across all cells.\nvec(M) produces the byte layout PhreeqcRM expects with no allocation.\n\nUse zeros_concentrations to construct the right shape:\n\nc = zeros_concentrations(rm)                   # Matrix{Float64}(nxyz(rm), ncomps(rm))\nget_concentrations!(rm, c)                     # zero-copy\n\nset_concentrations! and get_concentrations! validate the shape on every call. Passing the transposed shape would silently scramble data across cells — so the validator throws DimensionMismatch.","title":"Concentration matrix layout"},{"category":"section","location":"concepts/memory_model/#Hot-loop-allocation-rule","page":"Memory & layout","text":"The user's concentration matrix must be allocated once outside the time loop and reused via the in-place setters. The package guarantees zero allocations per call after warmup; this is asserted in the :perf test tier with @allocated == 0 on the full step (set_concentrations! + run_cells!\n\nget_concentrations!).\n\nc = zeros_concentrations(rm)        # allocate ONCE\nget_concentrations!(rm, c)\nfor step in 1:nsteps\n    transport!(c)\n    set_concentrations!(rm, c)\n    run_cells!(rm)\n    get_concentrations!(rm, c)      # no allocation\nend","title":"Hot-loop allocation rule"},{"category":"section","location":"concepts/memory_model/#Boundary-/-selected-output-buffers","page":"Memory & layout","text":"Same convention: items vary fastest, categories slowest.\n\ninitial_phreeqc_to_concentrations returns a Matrix{Float64}(n_boundaries, ncomps). Each row is one boundary solution.\nget_selected_output returns a NamedTuple of per-column vectors; the in-place form takes a Matrix{Float64}(nrows, ncols).","title":"Boundary / selected-output buffers"},{"category":"section","location":"reference/api/#API-reference","page":"Reference","text":"Auto-generated from docstrings.","title":"API reference"},{"category":"section","location":"reference/api/#Lifecycle","page":"Reference","text":"","title":"Lifecycle"},{"category":"section","location":"reference/api/#Errors","page":"Reference","text":"","title":"Errors"},{"category":"section","location":"reference/api/#Database-and-PHREEQC-input","page":"Reference","text":"","title":"Database and PHREEQC input"},{"category":"section","location":"reference/api/#Components","page":"Reference","text":"","title":"Components"},{"category":"section","location":"reference/api/#Units","page":"Reference","text":"(See also the per-domain enum modules: SolutionUnits, PPAssemblageUnits, ExchangeUnits, SurfaceUnits, GasPhaseUnits, SSAssemblageUnits, KineticsUnits.)","title":"Units"},{"category":"section","location":"reference/api/#Spatial-properties","page":"Reference","text":"The per-cell scalar setters all share the same signature f(rm, v::AbstractVector{<:Real}) where length(v) == nxyz(rm). They send the per-cell physical property to PhreeqcRM's internal store:\n\nset_porosity!(rm, v) — porosity (unitless)\nset_saturation!(rm, v) — saturation (unitless)\nset_representative_volume!(rm, v) — representative volume (L)\nset_temperature!(rm, v) — temperature (°C)\nset_pressure!(rm, v) — pressure (atm)\nset_density!(rm, v) — density (kg/L)","title":"Spatial properties"},{"category":"section","location":"reference/api/#Concentrations","page":"Reference","text":"","title":"Concentrations"},{"category":"section","location":"reference/api/#Initial-/-boundary-conditions","page":"Reference","text":"","title":"Initial / boundary conditions"},{"category":"section","location":"reference/api/#Time-stepping","page":"Reference","text":"","title":"Time stepping"},{"category":"section","location":"reference/api/#Selected-output","page":"Reference","text":"","title":"Selected output"},{"category":"section","location":"reference/api/#Threading","page":"Reference","text":"","title":"Threading"},{"category":"type","location":"reference/api/#PhreeqcRM.PhreeqcRMInstance","page":"Reference","text":"PhreeqcRMInstance(nxyz; nthreads=1, component_h2o=false)\n\nConstruct a PhreeqcRM instance covering nxyz reaction cells. Returns an opaque handle around an integer id and a small amount of Julia-side bookkeeping (no C-owned memory references).\n\nKeyword arguments:\n\nnthreads::Integer=1 — OpenMP thread count for the internal RunCells loop. The default is 1 to avoid OpenMP × Julia thread oversubscription. Set higher (or Threads.nthreads()) when reactions dominate runtime.\ncomponent_h2o::Bool=false — if true, water is tracked as its own component instead of being inferred from H and O moles. Affects the component list reported by find_components!. Must be set before load_database! — that's why it lives on the constructor.\n\nThe constructor does not create any output files. Use open_output! to enable *.chem.txt and *.log.txt logs.\n\nAlways pair with Base.close or use with_instance.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PhreeqcRM.PhreeqcRMInstance"},{"category":"function","location":"reference/api/#PhreeqcRM.with_instance","page":"Reference","text":"with_instance(f, nxyz; kwargs...)\n\nConstruct a PhreeqcRMInstance(nxyz; kwargs...), pass it to f, and close it on exit — including when f throws.\n\nwith_instance(40; nthreads=4) do rm\n    load_database!(rm, \"phreeqc.dat\")\n    run_file!(rm, \"advect.pqi\")\n    # ...\nend\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PhreeqcRM.with_instance"},{"category":"method","location":"reference/api/#Base.close-Tuple{PhreeqcRMInstance}","page":"Reference","text":"close(rm::PhreeqcRMInstance)\n\nDestroy the PhreeqcRM instance and release its OpenMP workers. Idempotent.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Base.close"},{"category":"function","location":"reference/api/#PhreeqcRM.open_output!","page":"Reference","text":"open_output!(rm; prefix, dir=pwd())\n\nOpen PhreeqcRM's text + log output files at joinpath(dir, prefix).chem.txt and .log.txt. Opt-in — the constructor does not create files.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PhreeqcRM.open_output!"},{"category":"function","location":"reference/api/#PhreeqcRM.close_output!","page":"Reference","text":"close_output!(rm)\n\nClose any output files previously opened with open_output!.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PhreeqcRM.close_output!"},{"category":"type","location":"reference/api/#PhreeqcRM.PhreeqcRMError","page":"Reference","text":"PhreeqcRMError <: Exception\n\nThrown by any wrapped RM_* call that returns a non-IRM_OK IRM_RESULT. Fields:\n\ncode::IRMResult — the underlying error code.\nmessage::String — the message accumulated by RM_GetErrorString.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PhreeqcRM.PhreeqcRMError"},{"category":"type","location":"reference/api/#PhreeqcRM.IRMResult","page":"Reference","text":"IRMResult\n\nAlias for the generated LibPhreeqcRM.IRM_RESULT enum. Values:\n\nIRM_OK            =  0\nIRM_OUTOFMEMORY   = -1\nIRM_BADVARTYPE    = -2\nIRM_INVALIDARG    = -3\nIRM_INVALIDROW    = -4\nIRM_INVALIDCOL    = -5\nIRM_BADINSTANCE   = -6\nIRM_FAIL          = -7\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PhreeqcRM.IRMResult"},{"category":"function","location":"reference/api/#PhreeqcRM.load_database!","page":"Reference","text":"load_database!(rm, path::AbstractString)\n\nRead a PHREEQC database file (e.g. phreeqc.dat, llnl.dat, pitzer.dat) into all the IPhreeqc instances inside rm. Must precede run_file!.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PhreeqcRM.load_database!"},{"category":"function","location":"reference/api/#PhreeqcRM.run_file!","page":"Reference","text":"run_file!(rm, path; workers=true, initial=true, utility=true)\n\nRun a PHREEQC input file against the selected IPhreeqc instances inside rm.\n\nworkers=true  — populate the worker IPhreeqc instances (the ones that do per-cell chemistry inside run_cells!).\ninitial=true  — populate the InitialPhreeqc instance, which holds the numbered SOLUTION / EXCHANGE / EQUILIBRIUM_PHASES definitions later referenced by set_initial_conditions!.\nutility=true  — populate the Utility instance.\n\nThe defaults match the common case: a PHREEQC script that defines the full chemistry. Call once before find_components!.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PhreeqcRM.run_file!"},{"category":"function","location":"reference/api/#PhreeqcRM.run_string!","page":"Reference","text":"run_string!(rm, input; workers=true, initial=true, utility=true)\n\nSame as run_file! but takes a PHREEQC input as a string. Useful for programmatically generated scripts or inline test fixtures.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PhreeqcRM.run_string!"},{"category":"function","location":"reference/api/#PhreeqcRM.find_components!","page":"Reference","text":"find_components!(rm) -> Vector{String}\n\nScan the InitialPhreeqc instance for every element / mass-balance component that has been defined by run_file! / run_string!, and cache the result on rm.\n\nMust be called before any set_concentrations! / get_concentrations! call because the concentration buffer is sized ncomps(rm) * nxyz(rm). Subsequent calls are cheap (results are cached).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PhreeqcRM.find_components!"},{"category":"function","location":"reference/api/#PhreeqcRM.components","page":"Reference","text":"components(rm) -> Vector{String}\n\nCached component names from the most recent find_components!. Throws if find_components! hasn't been called yet.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PhreeqcRM.components"},{"category":"function","location":"reference/api/#PhreeqcRM.ncomps","page":"Reference","text":"ncomps(rm) -> Int\n\nNumber of components in rm's chemistry. Zero until find_components! is called.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PhreeqcRM.ncomps"},{"category":"function","location":"reference/api/#PhreeqcRM.nxyz","page":"Reference","text":"nxyz(rm) -> Int\n\nNumber of reaction cells in rm (the value passed to the constructor).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PhreeqcRM.nxyz"},{"category":"function","location":"reference/api/#PhreeqcRM.set_units!","page":"Reference","text":"set_units!(rm; solution, pp_assemblage=..., exchange=..., surface=...,\n           gas_phase=..., ss_assemblage=..., kinetics=...)\n\nConfigure the unit convention for each reactant category. solution is required — its value determines how the numbers passed to set_concentrations! are interpreted (mg/L vs mol/L vs kg/kgs).\n\nAll *_assemblage / exchange / surface / gas_phase / kinetics units default to mol/L of rock volume.\n\nEach keyword takes a value from the matching enum: SolutionUnits.MolPerL, PPAssemblageUnits.MolPerLRock, etc.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PhreeqcRM.set_units!"},{"category":"function","location":"reference/api/#PhreeqcRM.set_mapping!","page":"Reference","text":"set_mapping!(rm, grid2chem::AbstractVector{<:Integer})\n\nMap each of nxyz transport cells to a reaction cell index. -1 marks an inactive transport cell that should not be reacted. Default mapping is identity (collect(0:nxyz-1)); call this only if you need to skip cells or collapse multiple transport cells onto one reaction cell.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PhreeqcRM.set_mapping!"},{"category":"function","location":"reference/api/#PhreeqcRM.zeros_concentrations","page":"Reference","text":"zeros_concentrations(rm) -> Matrix{Float64}\n\nAllocate a fresh concentration matrix sized (nxyz(rm), ncomps(rm)), initialized to zero. This is the recommended constructor — passing the wrong shape to set_concentrations! is an error, but constructing this way makes the contract self-enforcing.\n\nEach row holds one cell; each column holds one component across cells.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PhreeqcRM.zeros_concentrations"},{"category":"function","location":"reference/api/#PhreeqcRM.set_concentrations!","page":"Reference","text":"set_concentrations!(rm, c::AbstractMatrix{Float64})\n\nSend the per-cell, per-component concentrations to PhreeqcRM. c must have shape (nxyz(rm), ncomps(rm)) and contiguous strides — the recommended way to allocate it is zeros_concentrations. Validated, zero-copy in the happy path.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PhreeqcRM.set_concentrations!"},{"category":"function","location":"reference/api/#PhreeqcRM.get_concentrations","page":"Reference","text":"get_concentrations(rm) -> Matrix{Float64}\n\nAllocating convenience that returns a fresh Matrix{Float64}(ncomps, nxyz) filled with current concentrations. Do not call inside a hot loop — use get_concentrations! with a pre-allocated buffer instead.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PhreeqcRM.get_concentrations"},{"category":"function","location":"reference/api/#PhreeqcRM.get_concentrations!","page":"Reference","text":"get_concentrations!(rm, c::AbstractMatrix{Float64})\n\nPull the post-reaction concentrations from PhreeqcRM into the caller's buffer c. Shape and contiguity requirements match set_concentrations!. In-place — does not allocate. This is what the hot loop should use.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PhreeqcRM.get_concentrations!"},{"category":"function","location":"reference/api/#PhreeqcRM.bycell","page":"Reference","text":"bycell(c::AbstractMatrix{Float64})\n\nIterator over per-cell row views of a concentration matrix (nxyz, ncomps). Each element is a view (no copy) of length ncomps. Convenient for per-cell inspection:\n\nfor (icell, cell) in enumerate(bycell(c))\n    @show icell, cell[1]   # first component in this cell\nend\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PhreeqcRM.bycell"},{"category":"function","location":"reference/api/#PhreeqcRM.set_initial_conditions!","page":"Reference","text":"set_initial_conditions!(rm; solution=fill(-1, nxyz(rm)),\n                            equilibrium_phases=..., exchange=...,\n                            surface=..., gas_phase=...,\n                            ss_assemblage=..., kinetics=...)\n\nAssign numbered reactant blocks (defined in the PHREEQC script previously loaded with run_file!) to each of the nxyz cells.\n\nEach keyword takes an integer vector of length nxyz — entry i is the PHREEQC user number of the block to use in cell i, or -1 to leave that slot empty.\n\nUnspecified categories default to -1 in every cell.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PhreeqcRM.set_initial_conditions!"},{"category":"function","location":"reference/api/#PhreeqcRM.initial_phreeqc_to_concentrations","page":"Reference","text":"initial_phreeqc_to_concentrations(rm; solution::AbstractVector{<:Integer}) -> Matrix{Float64}\n\nTranslate a list of SOLUTION N definitions from the InitialPhreeqc instance into a concentration matrix of shape (length(solution), ncomps(rm)) — same layout convention as zeros_concentrations: each row is one boundary solution, each column is one component.\n\nTypical use: build the inflow/boundary concentration vector(s) for transport without touching any cell:\n\nbc = initial_phreeqc_to_concentrations(rm; solution=[0])   # SOLUTION 0, 1×ncomps\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PhreeqcRM.initial_phreeqc_to_concentrations"},{"category":"function","location":"reference/api/#PhreeqcRM.set_time!","page":"Reference","text":"set_time!(rm, t::Real)\n\nSet the current simulation time (PhreeqcRM-internal seconds by default).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PhreeqcRM.set_time!"},{"category":"function","location":"reference/api/#PhreeqcRM.set_time_step!","page":"Reference","text":"set_time_step!(rm, dt::Real)\n\nSet the time step over which the next run_cells! call will integrate kinetic reactants. Must be called before run_cells! or kinetics integrate over zero time.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PhreeqcRM.set_time_step!"},{"category":"function","location":"reference/api/#PhreeqcRM.run_cells!","page":"Reference","text":"run_cells!(rm)\n\nRun the reaction calculation on every active cell, in parallel across PhreeqcRM's OpenMP workers. The current cell concentrations are read from the buffer last seen by set_concentrations!; the post-reaction concentrations are stored in PhreeqcRM's internal buffer, retrievable with get_concentrations!.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PhreeqcRM.run_cells!"},{"category":"function","location":"reference/api/#PhreeqcRM.enable_selected_output!","page":"Reference","text":"enable_selected_output!(rm, on::Bool)\n\nTurn the recording of SELECTED_OUTPUT columns on or off. Defaults to off in the upstream library. Call before run_cells! to get fresh values out of get_selected_output.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PhreeqcRM.enable_selected_output!"},{"category":"function","location":"reference/api/#PhreeqcRM.get_selected_output","page":"Reference","text":"get_selected_output(rm) -> NamedTuple\n\nReturn the current SELECTED_OUTPUT table as a NamedTuple whose names are the column headings (as Symbols) and whose values are Vector{Float64} of length RM_GetSelectedOutputRowCount(rm) (which equals nxyz when the selected output is per cell).\n\nAllocates. Use get_selected_output! for hot paths.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PhreeqcRM.get_selected_output"},{"category":"function","location":"reference/api/#PhreeqcRM.selected_output_headings","page":"Reference","text":"selected_output_headings(rm) -> Vector{String}\n\nColumn names from the SELECTED_OUTPUT block. Cached on first call.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PhreeqcRM.selected_output_headings"},{"category":"function","location":"reference/api/#PhreeqcRM.get_solution_volume","page":"Reference","text":"get_solution_volume(rm) -> Vector{Float64}\n\nPer-cell solution volume (L) after the most recent run_cells!.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PhreeqcRM.get_solution_volume"},{"category":"function","location":"reference/api/#PhreeqcRM.get_density","page":"Reference","text":"get_density(rm) -> Vector{Float64}\n\nPer-cell solution density (kg/L) computed from the most recent run_cells!.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PhreeqcRM.get_density"},{"category":"function","location":"reference/api/#PhreeqcRM.get_saturation","page":"Reference","text":"get_saturation(rm) -> Vector{Float64}\n\nPer-cell saturation (unitless) computed from the most recent run_cells! — may differ from the value last passed to set_saturation! if mineral dissolution / precipitation changed the solution volume.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PhreeqcRM.get_saturation"},{"category":"function","location":"reference/api/#PhreeqcRM.thread_count","page":"Reference","text":"thread_count(rm) -> Int\n\nNumber of OpenMP threads PhreeqcRM is currently using for the per-cell reaction loop.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PhreeqcRM.thread_count"},{"category":"function","location":"reference/api/#PhreeqcRM.set_thread_count!","page":"Reference","text":"set_thread_count!(rm, n::Integer)\n\nChange PhreeqcRM's OpenMP thread count after construction. Generally simpler to set this via the constructor's nthreads= keyword.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PhreeqcRM.set_thread_count!"},{"category":"section","location":"installation/#Installation","page":"Installation","text":"The package is not registered yet. Until the Yggdrasil-built PhreeqcRM_jll exists you need to build libphreeqcrm locally.","title":"Installation"},{"category":"section","location":"installation/#1.-Build-libphreeqcrm","page":"Installation","text":"Requirements: CMake ≥ 3.13, a C++ compiler, and (on macOS) libomp from Homebrew.\n\ngit clone https://github.com/vcantarella/PhreeqcRM.jl.git\ncd PhreeqcRM.jl\nbash deps/build_phreeqcrm.sh\n\nThis clones the upstream USGS source at a pinned tag (v3.9.0), builds a shared library with OpenMP, and installs to deps/usr/.\n\nThe macOS build automatically picks up libomp from Homebrew if present. Without libomp, the dylib falls back to single-threaded and OpenMP-related tests are no-ops. Install with brew install libomp.","title":"1. Build libphreeqcrm"},{"category":"section","location":"installation/#2.-Point-Julia-at-the-library","page":"Installation","text":"export JULIA_PHREEQCRM_PATH=\"$PWD/deps/usr/lib/libPhreeqcRM.dylib\"   # macOS\n# Linux:   export JULIA_PHREEQCRM_PATH=\"$PWD/deps/usr/lib/libPhreeqcRM.so\"\n\nThe local PhreeqcRM_jll stub reads this env var at module load. When the Yggdrasil JLL ships, it'll be a one-line drop-in and the env var goes away.","title":"2. Point Julia at the library"},{"category":"section","location":"installation/#3.-Use-the-package","page":"Installation","text":"julia --project=PhreeqcRM\n\njulia> using PhreeqcRM\njulia> rm = PhreeqcRMInstance(10)\njulia> close(rm)","title":"3. Use the package"},{"category":"section","location":"#PhreeqcRM.jl","page":"Home","text":"Julia interface to USGS's PhreeqcRM, the reactive-transport reaction module bundled with PHREEQC. PhreeqcRM is a C++ class with a flat C façade (RM_* functions) designed to be the geochemistry step inside a transport simulator: each timestep the transport code calls SetConcentrations → RunCells → GetConcentrations.\n\nThis package wraps the C interface in two layers:\n\nLow level (PhreeqcRM.LibPhreeqcRM): Clang.jl-generated @ccalls, one-to-one with the C header. Regenerated from gen/generator.jl by maintainers.\nHigh level (the documented surface): PhreeqcRMInstance with a finalizer\nexplicit close, typed PhreeqcRMError exceptions, per-domain unit\n@enums, shape-validated concentration matrices, threading helpers.","title":"PhreeqcRM.jl"},{"category":"section","location":"#Quickstart","page":"Home","text":"using PhreeqcRM\n\nrm = PhreeqcRMInstance(40; nthreads = 1)\nload_database!(rm, \"/path/to/phreeqc.dat\")\nrun_string!(rm, \\\"\\\"\\\"\n    SOLUTION 1\n        pH 7.0\n        Na 1.0\n        Cl 1.0 charge\n    END\n\\\"\\\"\\\")\nset_units!(rm; solution = SolutionUnits.MolPerL)\nset_porosity!(rm,              fill(0.3, 40))\nset_saturation!(rm,            fill(1.0, 40))\nset_representative_volume!(rm, fill(1.0, 40))\nset_temperature!(rm,           fill(25.0, 40))\nset_pressure!(rm,              fill(1.0,  40))\nfind_components!(rm)\nset_initial_conditions!(rm; solution = fill(1, 40))\n\nc = zeros_concentrations(rm)               # Matrix(nxyz, ncomps)\nget_concentrations!(rm, c)\nset_time!(rm, 0.0); set_time_step!(rm, 60.0)\nrun_cells!(rm)\nget_concentrations!(rm, c)\nclose(rm)\n\nSee examples/advection_reaction.jl for a complete end-to-end column transport with cation exchange.","title":"Quickstart"},{"category":"section","location":"#Status","page":"Home","text":"Early. The local-build path (deps/build_phreeqcrm.sh) works on macOS and Linux; a Yggdrasil-built PhreeqcRM_jll is not yet published. Once the JLL ships, the local stub goes away with no source changes in this package.","title":"Status"},{"category":"section","location":"concepts/phreeqc_vs_phreeqcrm/#PHREEQC-vs-PhreeqcRM-—-where-chemistry-lives","page":"PHREEQC vs PhreeqcRM","text":"A common source of confusion: PhreeqcRM does not replace PHREEQC's input language. The chemistry — what minerals can precipitate, what exchange sites exist, what kinetic rate laws govern dissolution — is still defined in a PHREEQC input script using the same keyword blocks the standalone phreeqc CLI consumes. PhreeqcRM's job is to consume that script once and drive the per-cell chemistry calculations from a transport simulator.\n\nPhreeqcRM.jl does not expose SOLUTION / EXCHANGE / EQUILIBRIUM_PHASES etc. as Julia structs. Doing so would mean reimplementing PHREEQC's parser, which is large, evolving, and out of scope. You hand PhreeqcRM a .pqi file (or a string), and the Julia side controls which numbered solution / exchange / etc. lives in which cell.","title":"PHREEQC vs PhreeqcRM — where chemistry lives"},{"category":"section","location":"concepts/phreeqc_vs_phreeqcrm/#Where-each-concept-is-defined","page":"PHREEQC vs PhreeqcRM","text":"Concept Defined in Referenced from Julia\nElements, species, log K, Debye–Hückel Database file (phreeqc.dat, llnl.dat, …) load_database!\nNumbered SOLUTION (initial & boundary) Script run_file!, then set_initial_conditions!\nEQUILIBRIUM_PHASES, EXCHANGE, SURFACE Script set_initial_conditions! with equilibrium_phases=…, etc.\nGAS_PHASE, SOLID_SOLUTIONS Script set_initial_conditions!\nKINETICS + RATES (Basic rate-law code) Script set_initial_conditions! with kinetics=…\nWhich columns to retrieve Script: SELECTED_OUTPUT 1 … enable_selected_output! + get_selected_output\nNumber of cells (nxyz) Julia PhreeqcRMInstance constructor\nCell mapping Julia set_mapping!\nPorosity, saturation, T, P, density Julia (per timestep if you want) set_porosity!, set_saturation!, etc.\nComponent concentrations per cell Julia (every transport step) set_concentrations! / get_concentrations!\nTime and time step Julia set_time!, set_time_step!","title":"Where each concept is defined"},{"category":"section","location":"concepts/phreeqc_vs_phreeqcrm/#Worked-example","page":"PHREEQC vs PhreeqcRM","text":"using PhreeqcRM\n\nrm = PhreeqcRMInstance(40)\nload_database!(rm, \"phreeqc.dat\")\n\n# All chemistry — solutions, exchange site capacity, what to record —\n# is in the PHREEQC script:\nrun_string!(rm, \\\"\\\"\\\"\n    SOLUTION 0    Inflow water\n        units mmol/kgw\n        pH 7.0\n        Ca 1.0\n        Cl 2.0 charge\n    SOLUTION 1-40 Initial column water\n        units mmol/kgw\n        pH 7.0\n        Na 1.0\n        Cl 1.0 charge\n    EXCHANGE 1-40\n        -equilibrate 1\n        X 0.0011\n    SELECTED_OUTPUT 1\n        -reset false\n        -pH    true\n        -totals Na Ca Cl\n    END\n\\\"\\\"\\\")\n\n# Geometry, time, transport, units — Julia's responsibility:\nset_units!(rm; solution = SolutionUnits.KgPerKgSolution)\nset_porosity!(rm, fill(0.3, 40))\n# ... per-cell setters ...\nfind_components!(rm)\nset_initial_conditions!(rm; solution = collect(1:40), exchange = collect(1:40))\n\nThe Julia code never names \"calcite\" or \"Gaines-Thomas convention\" — those are entirely the script's concern. The Julia code controls geometry, time, transport, and result extraction.","title":"Worked example"},{"category":"section","location":"devnotes/regenerating_bindings/#Regenerating-the-low-level-bindings","page":"Regenerating bindings","text":"src/LibPhreeqcRM.jl is generated by Clang.jl from the vendored C header gen/include/RM_interface_C.h. The generated file is committed, so users do not regenerate at install time — only maintainers do, when upstream changes.","title":"Regenerating the low-level bindings"},{"category":"section","location":"devnotes/regenerating_bindings/#When-to-regenerate","page":"Regenerating bindings","text":"Upstream usgs-coupled/phreeqcrm ships a new release.\nA new C function is needed by the high-level wrapper.","title":"When to regenerate"},{"category":"section","location":"devnotes/regenerating_bindings/#How","page":"Regenerating bindings","text":"# 1. Bump the PHREEQCRM_TAG in deps/build_phreeqcrm.sh and rebuild.\nPHREEQCRM_TAG=v3.10.0 bash deps/build_phreeqcrm.sh\n\n# 2. Re-vendor the header.\ncp deps/usr/include/RM_interface_C.h    gen/include/\ncp deps/usr/include/IrmResult.h         gen/include/\ncp deps/usr/include/irm_dll_export.h    gen/include/\n\n# 3. Regenerate the bindings.\njulia --project=gen gen/generator.jl\n\n# 4. Verify the diff in src/LibPhreeqcRM.jl makes sense.\ngit diff src/LibPhreeqcRM.jl","title":"How"},{"category":"section","location":"devnotes/regenerating_bindings/#What-can-go-wrong","page":"Regenerating bindings","text":"Caller-allocated char* typed as Cstring: Clang.jl turns every char * in the header into Cstring, which only accepts NUL-terminated strings on the way in. Output buffers we caller-allocate (component names, selected-output headings, error strings) need to bypass this and pass pointer(buf)::Ptr{UInt8} instead. The wrapper does this in a few spots — search for @ccall Lib.libphreeqcrm.RM_GetComponent etc.\nMacro definitions: IRM_DLL_EXPORT and friends are visibility attributes that don't translate. generator.toml sets macro_mode = \"disable\" to skip all #define translation.","title":"What can go wrong"}]
}
